{
  "texts": [
    "The precision and accuracy required in orthopedic procedures, such as joint replacements or fracture fixations, poses additional challenges.",
    "While AI models can simulate scenarios, their capacity to offer realistic, practical surgical guidance remains limited due to a lack of procedural understanding, experience and the complexities involved in orthopedic surgery.",
    "Section 6: Ethical and regulatory considerations in the use of generative AI in orthopedic trainingThe use of generative AI in orthopedic training requires careful ethical and regulatory considerations.",
    "Ensuring data privacy and protection is crucial, especially in in compliance with regulations such as GDPR (General Data Protection Regulation), which restrict unauthorized sharing of personal and patient information [153].",
    "The potential for algorithmic bias must be carefully assessed and mitigated to avoid reinforcing societal stereotypes and ensuring fair, unbiased education [154]."
  ]
}